{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes for Primary/Secondary TNs; modify Zeroth TN to frame \"ultimate reality\" as traditional reference, not endorsement",
    "content": "**Yes, with one modification: change the TN for Zeroth Reality.**\n\n\"Primary\" for First and \"Secondary\" for Second are fine as TN glosses. They restate the ordinal relationship in plain English without adding philosophical content. A reader who finds \"First Reality\" and \"Second Reality\" opaque can glance at the footnote and see \"Primary\" and \"Secondary,\" which clarifies the structural relationship (primary = starting point, secondary = derived from the primary). No harm done.\n\nBut \"Ultimate Reality\" for Zeroth Reality is still problematic, even in a footnote. The whole point of the Zeroth is that it is the *posited but inaccessible* ground --- the thing traditional metaphysics calls \"ultimate reality\" but which the author argues we can never reach. Glossing it as \"Ultimate Reality\" in a TN risks the reader thinking: \"Ah, so the author believes in an ultimate reality but calls it Zeroth.\" The author's position is closer to: \"This is what would be ultimate reality *if it existed for us*, but it doesn't --- the moment we articulate it, it becomes Second Reality.\"\n\n**Suggested modification:** TN for Zeroth Reality should be something like \"the posited ground; what traditional metaphysics calls 'ultimate reality'\" --- framing it as a reference to the tradition rather than an endorsement. This preserves the informational value (the reader learns what philosophical role the Zeroth plays) without implying the author accepts it as genuinely ultimate."
  }
}
